@node not11 "PROJECT OPERA FOR AMIGA HAS BEEN PUT ON HOLD"

@{B}PROJECT OPERA@{UB} FOR @{B}AMIGA@{UB} HAS BEEN PUT ON HOLD
--------------------------------------------

As you probably know there are three major browsers for @{B}Amiga@{UB}: @{B}Aweb@{UB}, @{B}Ibrowse@{UB} and
@{B}Voyager@{UB}.  Taking into account that the conversion of @{B}Netscape@{UB} for @{B}Amiga@{UB} seems to
be  not  viable, another option was the conversion of the @{B}Opera@{UB} browser. As this
conversion  was  oficially  announced  in May and we heard no news from then on,
probably you have been waiting patiently for news from the @{B}Amiga@{UB} versions.

According  to  @{I}Tim  Corringham@{UI},  the  head  of  the @{B}Amiga@{UB} development team, that
project  has  been  put  on  hold  because the entire @{B}Amiga@{UB} market seems to have
collapsed.  Mags  have gone out of business, no new information about the future
is forthcoming, and sales are next to dead.

They  are  now waiting for the Cologne Fair to see if it's worth continuing with
the project of stopping it altogether.

While the @{B}BeOS@{UB} and @{B}Psion@{UB} version are making good progress, and the project @{B}Magic@{UB}
initiator & coordinator, is confident that the very same will happen with @{B}MacOS@{UB},
@{B}OS/2@{UB}  and  @{B}Linux@{UB} (they will just take longer than anticipated), @{B}Amiga@{UB} remains to
be  seen.  The  market  is  still  out  there,  but  if it's not growing or even
remaining  stagnant,  then there may be little point in continuing, although the
initial   response   from  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  community  has  been  very  positive  and
encouraging.

Now  if you think that prefunding the individual projects is indeed a good idea,
then please let it know at @{I}magic@operasoftware.com@{UI}
