@node not12 "MUIBASE V1.0 ANNOUNCED"

@{B}MUIBASE V1.0@{UB} ANNOUNCED
----------------------

@{I}FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE@{UI}

Freiburg (Germany), 26. October 1998.

Dear @{B}Amiga@{UB}-Community,

I  am  very  pleased  to  announce  the  availability  of  @{B}MUIbase  V1.0@{UB}, a new,
relational,  flexible  and  very powerful database for the @{B}Amiga@{UB} system. @{B}MUIbase@{UB}
uses  -  as  you  might  already  have  guessed - the @{B}Magic User Interface@{UB} for a
powerful  and  highly  customize-able  user  interface.  This  together with its
internal  programming  language,  which uses a lisp-oriented paradigm, gives you
the maximum control and power for organizing and maintaining your personal data,
ranging  from  storing your CD-collections to fully-automated finance management
systems.  @{B}MUIbase@{UB} also offers SELECT-FROM-WHERE queries, a must-have feature for
relational databases!

As  of  today  no similar database package has been shown up that offers similar
capabilities  than  @{B}MUIbase@{UB}! Check it out, a demo version is available on @{B}Aminet@{UB}
or from:
@{B}http://www.amigaworld.com/support/muibase/@{UB}

@{I}Steffen Gutmann@{UI}

@{I}Features@{UI}

@{B}MUIbase@{UB}  is a fast and very flexible database for the @{B}Amiga@{UB}. It is for users who
want to manage data in a comfortable and easy way. @{B}MUIbase@{UB} is able to manage any
kind of data, e.g. addresses, CD series, movies, or your income and expense. The
power of @{B}MUIbase@{UB} lies in its clear and powerful graphical user interface and its
programming   capabilities.  The  latter  makes  it  possible  to  automatically
calculate and maintain nearly everything, starting from automatically summing up
values,  e.g.  for calculating the total amount of income or the total amount of
recorded time of a CD, up to automatically creating and printing letters for any
purpose.

@{B}MUIbase@{UB}  is  the  successor  of  @{B}AmigaBase@{UB}, a hierarchical programmable database
which is still available but considered obsolete with the appearance of @{B}MUIbase@{UB}.
All registered users of @{B}AmigaBase@{UB} can get a free upgrade to @{B}MUIbase@{UB}.

@{B}MUIbase@{UB} offers the following features:
  * Handling of multiple projects at the same time.
  * Attributes  can  be  of  type string, memo (multi line text), integer, real,
    date,  time,  bool, choice (one item out of many items), reference (easy way
    to  reference  a  record  of  another  table),  button (for starting @{B}MUIbase@{UB}
    programs), and virtual (compute value on the fly).
  * The string type can also manage lists of strings, files, and fonts. An @{B}OS3.x@{UB}
    datatype gadget allows displaying external images.
  * Unlimited number of records.
  * Dynamic  loading  of  records.  Records  which are not needed may be flushed
    from memory (e.g. when memory is low).
  * Programmability.  With  the  easy  and powerful @{B}MUIbase@{UB} programming language
    complex   tasks   can   be   implemented.   The  language  also  includes  a
    SELECT-FROM-WHERE query for easy and fast data retrieval.
  * Ordering of records by any combinations of attributes.
  * Flexible and powerful search and filter facility.
  * Query  editor  which  allows  entering  and  managing  of  SELECT-FROM-WHERE
    queries. The queries can be saved and the results can be printed.
  * Import and export facility.
  * Uses  @{B}MUI@{UB}  as user interface. The interface is highly customizable. External
    images can be included in the user interface.
  * Portability.  @{B}MUIbase@{UB}  development  has  been  done  under  the idea of easy
    portability.  The  system/gui  part  has been separated from the ANSI/C part
    such  that  porting @{B}MUIbase@{UB} will result in only porting the system/gui part.
    This is no promise that @{B}MUIbase@{UB} will ever get ported to another system, only
    the porting task has been made easier but may still be complicated depending
    on the target system/gui. But, indeed, I am thinking of a @{B}Java@{UB} port.

The unregistered version of @{B}MUIbase@{UB} is crippled in several ways. See the @{B}MUIbase@{UB}
documentation for a list of limitations in the unregistered version.

--
@{I}Steffen Gutmann@{UI}
@{I}gutmann@informatik.uni-freiburg.de@{UI}
