@node not32 "FMSX AMIGA 2.0 RELEASED!"

@{B}FMSX AMIGA 2.0@{UB} RELEASED!
------------------------

@{I}TITLE@{UI}

fMSX Amiga 2.0

@{I}AUTHOR@{UI}

@{I}Hans Guijt@{UI} (@{I}hguijt@inter.nl.net@{UI})

@{I}DESCRIPTION@{UI}

@{B}fMSX Amiga@{UB} emulates an @{B}MSX@{UB} computer on an @{B}Amiga@{UB}. Features include:
  * Full emulation of the @{B}MSX1@{UB} system.
  * Full emulation of the @{B}MSX2@{UB} system.
  * Support for reading/writing @{B}MSX@{UB} disks and disk images.
  * Can play all types of @{B}MSX@{UB} ROMs, including ROMs bigger than 32KB.
  * Support for the @{B}PSG@{UB}, @{B}SCC@{UB}, and @{B}FM-Pac@{UB} sound chips (through @{B}AHI@{UB} or native).
  * Support for @{B}MSX@{UB} memory sizes of up to 4Mb.
  * Can be controlled through @{B}ARexx@{UB}.

'@{UB}MSX@{UB}'  is  an  8-bit  computer  system with surprisingly good graphics and sound
capabilities.  How does graphic resolutions of up to 512 * 424, up to 256 colors
on screen, and 9 channel music sound?

To  demonstrate,  several @{UB}MSX@{UB} pictures (taken from @{UB}fMSX@{UB} while running) have been
uploaded to @{B}aminet@{UB} (pix/illu/msx_emu.lha).

Software  is not included with the package, but many packages (mostly games) can
be found on FTP sites:
     @{B}ftp.saitama-u.ac.jp/pub/msx/@{UB}
     @{B}altair.komkon.com/pub/MSX/@{UB}
     @{B}ftp.funet.fi/pub/msx/@{UB}
     @{B}riaph.irkutsk.su/pub/@{UB}

Hundreds  of  games  are  available  from  these  sites,  and some form a worthy
addition to the @{B}Amiga@{UB} software collection.

Of course @{UB}fMSX Amiga@{UB} is fully multitasking, runs in an intuition screen, and has
a font-sensitive, resizable user interface.

@{I}NEW FEATURES@{UI}

A  year  and a half in the making, you might expect a few changes. Well, nothing
is further from the truth!

This  version  of @{B}fMSX@{UB} is almost a new program. Entire modules were written from
scratch, most notably the video and CPU emulations.

Most  spectacular from a code point of view is the Dynamic Recompiler. This is a
complicated   piece   of   software  that  turns  @{B}Z80@{UB}  instructions  into  @{B}680x0@{UB}
instructions  on  the  fly,  before  executing them. Translated instructions are
cached  and  reused  when  needed. The net result? More configurability and more
speed.  Unfortunately,  it  is not yet as compatible as the old @{B}Z80@{UB} emulator, so
some  games  will not run on it. @{B}68060@{UB} owners will love it though, as it can run
at very precise speeds (previous versions could be astonishingly fast on @{B}68060@{UB}).

Also  rewritten  from  scratch  were  the display routines. Two complete sets of
routines  are now available, one for native screens (taking a few shortcuts here
and  there  for extra speed) and one for @{B}CyberGfx@{UB} mode. All @{B}MSX2@{UB} screenmodes are
supported  now, and every sprite resolution is available. The new routines are a
lot faster than before too.

Something that is _very_ useful for gamers: @{B}fMSX@{UB} can now turn a directory filled
with  @{B}MSX@{UB}  software  into  a temporary disk on the fly. Just enter the name of a
directory  into  one  of the "drive" gadgets, and the contents of that directory
are  written onto a temporary disk, ready for your use. @{UB}fMSX@{UB} will even detect if
you need any system files, and add these automatically if required!

The  GUI  was  completely  changed. Many gadgets were given places that are more
logical (I have had quite a few complaints about this, let me tell you). The new
GUI uses the BOOPSI gadgets which are in development for @{B}Merapi@{UB}, the Java system
by @{B}Haage&Partner@{UB}. I consider @{B}fMSX@{UB} a sort of field-test, a useful testbench while
@{B}Merapi@{UB} is still waiting off stage.

Add  in support for an @{B}MSX@{UB} mouse, and (very preliminary) support for the @{B}FM-Pac@{UB}.
Add in some nifty configuration options (such as custom interrupt speeds for the
ultimate  in speed control), and a cheat finder. Add in the fact that nothing of
note  seems  to  get uploaded to @{B}Aminet@{UB} recently. All in all, it should be clear
that you simply have no choice other than to get this emulator!

@{I}SPECIAL REQUIREMENTS@{UI}

All  this  power does, unfortunately, not come without a price. Memory usage has
skyrocketed,  don't  bother  to  apply with less than 3MB. A hefty processor was
always  useful,  and  that  is still true although it should run a bit better on
slower systems as well.

@{B}fMSX@{UB}  now once again requires @{B}AmigaOS 3.0@{UB}. It could never have worked on @{B}AmigaOS
2.0@{UB},  but  since  I  didn't  receive  a single bug report I can only assume that
nobody  was  using  it. Don't bother complaining, there is a lot of @{B}3.0@{UB} stuff in
there now and I won't be taking it out.

@{B}AHI@{UB} is required for some of the sound modes.

@{I}AVAILABILITY@{UI}

@{B}fMSX    Amiga    2.0@{UB}   is   available   from   any   @{B}aminet@{UB}   site,   such   as:
@{B}ftp://ftp.wustl.edu/pub/aminet/misc/emu/fmsx_2.0.lha@{UB}

@{I}PRICE@{UI}

All this, for free!

@{I}DISTRIBUTABILITY@{UI}

@{B}fMSX Amiga 2.0@{UB} is publically supported freeware.

Source  for  previous  versions  was available on request. However, this version
contains  some  code for @{B}Merapi@{UB} which I am not willing to share at this point in
time. You can get the source, but without the BOOPSI gadgets.

Depending on how things go with @{B}Merapi@{UB} this may change in the future.
