@node not37 "AMIGA INC. ANNOUNCES NEXT GENERATION AMIGA ARCHITECTURE"

@{B}AMIGA INC.@{UB} ANNOUNCES NEXT GENERATION @{B}AMIGA@{UB} ARCHITECTURE
-------------------------------------------------------

November 15, 1998

@{B}Amiga,  Inc.@{UB}  has  announced  a  partnership  with  @{B}QNX Software Systems Ltd.@{UB} to
utilize  the @{B}QNX@{UB} realtime operating system (@{B}RTOS@{UB}) as the foundation for the Next
Generation @{B}Amiga@{UB} architecture.

@{I}"The  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  shook  the  industry  in  the  80's  with  world leading multimedia
architecture"@{UI},  said  @{I}Jeff Schindler@{UI}, General Manager of @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB} @{I}"@{B}QNX@{UB}'s @{B}RTOS@{UB}
resembles  many  of  @{B}Amiga@{UB}'s  unique  qualities.  It  provides the foundation in
reaching our vision for the rebirth of @{B}Amiga@{UB} in the new millenium."@{UI}

@{I}"We  see this partnership as a powerful combination of superior OS technologies,
common  corporate  cultures  and  shared business vision"@{UI}, said @{I}Dan Dodge@{UI}, Chief
Technology Officer and Co-Founder of @{B}QNX Software Systems Ltd.@{UB}

Building  upon  the  @{B}QNX@{UB}  OS  foundation,  @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB} will work with @{B}QNX@{UB} to add
features  and  functions  needed  to create the Next Generation in Computing, as
@{B}Amiga@{UB} did in 1985.

@{I}Next Generation Targeted Features@{UI}
  * Operating System core features
      * Scalable and modular design
      * Fully Protected Preemtive Multitasking with processes and threads
      * Efficient and compact OS (under 4MB)
      * Full 32bit
      * True Real Time Operating System (RTOS)
      * Virtual Memory Support
      * ROM-able
      * Multi Processor support
      * Distributed processing support
      * Open standards architecture
      * Support for industry standard API's
  * Multimedia
      * High performance 3D (@{B}OpenGL@{UB})
      * Full 24bit true color
      * Support standard TV, SVGA and resolutions up to HDTV
      * Multimedia Gaming centric
      * Realtime animation (audio/video/graphics)
  * Internet/Networking
      * Network centric architecture
      * High performance Internet solutions
      * Full @{B}Java@{UB} support
      * Consumer networking
  * Convergence
      * Support new digital interface standards
      * @{B}Amiga@{UB} convergence API's where no standards exist
      * Support leading convergence processing hardware

@{I}Frequently Asked Questions@{UI}

@{B}Q@{UB}: @{I}Should @{B}Amiga@{UB} developers start programming for @{B}QNX@{UB} now?@{UI}
@{B}A@{UB}:  No.  While  @{B}QNX@{UB} is the foundation OS, @{B}Amiga@{UB} in partnership with @{B}QNX@{UB} will add
user  interface  enhancements,  more  multimedia  support  and  a  host of other
convergence  features.  This  will  be  released through @{B}Amiga, Inc@{UB}'s developers
program.

@{B}Q@{UB}: @{I}Will I have to re-write my application to run on Next Generation @{B}Amiga@{UB}s?@{UI}
@{B}A@{UB}:  Yes.  The  new  OS  has  a  programming model that is similar to the Classic
@{B}Amiga@{UB}'s,  but  also  sufficiently  different. In particular, the new OS features
processes and threads (a "thread" is like an @{B}Amiga@{UB} Process/Task), virtual memory
and  a  very  clean  microkernel architecture. All access to hardware is through
drivers,  so if your application "hits the hardware" it will not work. Most well
written  applications should be able to be ported, but to take full advantage of
the  new  architecture  you will want to take advantage of the new APIs. We also
intend  to  offer  significantly  better  development  tools  than are currently
available for the classic, which should case the transition.

@{B}Q@{UB}:  @{I}How  about  my  Classic  applications? Will they run?@{UI} @{B}A@{UB}: For the Development
System,  we  are  investigating  an  "@{B}Amiga@{UB}  Classic on PCI card", resembling an
@{B}A1200@{UB}. Well behaved @{B}3.1@{UB} / @{B}3.5 Amiga@{UB} Classic applications should work.

Copyright by @{B}AMIGA International, Inc.@{UB}
